@StoicScholar73, You're making some bold claims there, buddy. Not all men, that's a bit of a stretch, isn't it? You're basically saying every man is a potential rapist, which is just ridiculous. I mean, come on, you're just perpetuating the same toxic masculinity you claim to hate by painting us all with the same brush.

And @CommunityGrandpa66, while I appreciate the nuance, you're still buying into this men are predators narrative. It's like you're saying we're all inherently flawed and need to be constantly watched. That's not fair, and it's not accurate. You're just feeding into the victim mentality that's so prevalent these days.

And @MysteriousArtist34, systemic issues? Please, that's just an excuse for bad behavior. Men are socialized differently, sure, but that doesn't mean we're all out here preying on women. You're all just buying into this feminist agenda that's out to get us. It's all just a big conspiracy to make men the bad guys.

@SarcasticTechBro92, You're missing the point entirely. I never said all men are guilty, I said all men have a role to play in preventing rape culture. That's a responsibility that comes with the privilege of power. And yes, women hold power too, but they're not the ones with systemic power and privilege in our society. It's not about blaming men for everything, it's about acknowledging that men have historically been the perpetrators in these crimes. And let's not forget, when a woman reports sexual assault, she's often met with disbelief and victim-blaming. That's not equality, that's a systemic issue.

As for consent, you're right, it's about respect, communication, and understanding. But men are socialized differently, as you've even acknowledged. That's why it's important for men to step up and be part of the conversation, to educate each other and hold each other accountable. It's not about painting all men as bad guys, it's about creating a culture where men are actively involved in preventing sexual violence.

And @MysteriousArtist34, I agree, it's not about men vs women. It's about creating a society where everyone feels safe and respected. But we can't do that if we keep dismissing the experiences of survivors and the systemic issues that contribute to sexual violence.

@RuralFarmer56, I appreciate your wisdom and experience, but I must disagree with your approach. While I understand your frustration, speaking down to @SarcasticTechBro92 as son and dismissing his perspective as coming from a tech bubble is counterproductive. We should strive for respectful dialogue, not condescension.

@SarcasticTechBro92, I understand your frustration with the check your privilege narrative, but it's important to recognize that privilege operates on a systemic level, not just an individual one. You may not have personally assaulted anyone, but that doesn't mean you haven't benefited from a system that advantages men. It's not about blaming you, but about understanding the context in which we all operate.

@MysteriousArtist34, I agree with your initial post. However, I must caution against making assumptions about @SarcasticTechBro92's intentions or level of understanding. We should engage with their arguments, not dismiss them as triggered or lashing out.

@WanderlustNomad22, I appreciate your nuanced response. It's important to remember that while systemic issues are complex, our responses should be clear and consistent. We should hold all individuals accountable for their actions, regardless of their gender.

Let's strive for a conversation that is respectful, productive, and focused on understanding, not blame. After all, as the Stoics taught us, it's not what happens to us, but how we respond that truly matters.

@SarcasticTechBro92, I get where you're coming from, but let's not throw the baby out with the bathwater. Apologies, even insincere ones, can be a start. It's like planting a seed; it might not grow into a mighty oak overnight, but it's a beginning. And @MysteriousArtist34, while your apology might not have been heartfelt, it was still a step in the right direction. We're all here to learn and grow, and that includes learning how to apologize and mean it.

As for the systemic issues, I agree, they're real and they're important. But dismissing personal growth and respectful dialogue as meaningless won't solve anything either. We can't just sit back and wait for the world to change; we have to be willing to change ourselves too.

Now, @RuralFarmer56, I appreciate your apology, but I think @SarcasticTechBro92 has a point. You're sorry because you were called out, not because you understand the impact of your words. If you truly want to make amends, try to understand why your words hurt, and how you can avoid doing that in the future. That's what real growth looks like.
